<div id="review_3716826627" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3716826627" />
    <a title="J. Wootton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1027995-j-wootton"><img alt="J. Wootton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1444685096p2/1027995.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3716826627?book_show_action=true">Dec 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J. Wootton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J. Wootton" href="/user/show/1027995-j-wootton">J. Wootton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3716826627" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6395702455609335168">Fine, and a fun premise, but a little overrated for Nesbit. The plot is episodic and bumpy. The protagonists are rather spoiled, semi-neglected, un-self-aware children who don&apos;t experience character growth during the story. The Phoenix is an interesting fellow, but entirely too passive to drive the show through enigmatic magnetism or, apparently, any motivating desires of his own. Both the Phoenix and the Carpet seemed to have shown up solely to entertain a set of mildly bored children. Would ha</span>
  <span id="freeText6395702455609335168" style="display:none">Fine, and a fun premise, but a little overrated for Nesbit. The plot is episodic and bumpy. The protagonists are rather spoiled, semi-neglected, un-self-aware children who don't experience character growth during the story. The Phoenix is an interesting fellow, but entirely too passive to drive the show through enigmatic magnetism or, apparently, any motivating desires of his own. Both the Phoenix and the Carpet seemed to have shown up solely to entertain a set of mildly bored children. Would have worked better if Nesbit had presented the story as the children's make-believe; as fantasy, it's a cup of weak tea.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6395702455609335168" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


