<div id="review_3533959939" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3533959939" />
    <a title="Shawn Thrasher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2148308-shawn-thrasher"><img alt="Shawn Thrasher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1549498919p2/2148308.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3533959939?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shawn Thrasher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shawn Thrasher" href="/user/show/2148308-shawn-thrasher">Shawn Thrasher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/21382695-the-phoenix-and-the-carpet">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3533959939" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11258843585991183889">The five children from Nesbit&apos;s Five Children and It find a phoenix and a magic wishing carpet, and similar hilarity to their previous jaunt ensues. While not quite as strong as the first - the phoenix is not quite as fun as the psammead - there is still Nesbit&apos;s signature sharp humor and sense of fun. I definitely always think she&apos;s ahead of her time as a writer. There is nothing treacly or good-two-shoes about Nesbit&apos;s writing; if there are morals, they are not in your face. Five Children and </span>
  <span id="freeText11258843585991183889" style="display:none">The five children from Nesbit's Five Children and It find a phoenix and a magic wishing carpet, and similar hilarity to their previous jaunt ensues. While not quite as strong as the first - the phoenix is not quite as fun as the psammead - there is still Nesbit's signature sharp humor and sense of fun. I definitely always think she's ahead of her time as a writer. There is nothing treacly or good-two-shoes about Nesbit's writing; if there are morals, they are not in your face. Five Children and It is laugh out loud; this second book will make you smile broadly and continue to appreciate Nesbit's writing style. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11258843585991183889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
